Fighting on the verge: MP3 players versus mobiles.
We help you to choose
While almost all mobiles are capable of playing MP3 files, no MP3 player can be phoned.
It seems clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
However, there are many reasons why a person can get a separate MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the needs of the prospective owner.
It’s probably hard to get a high-end home recording player to listen to that latest Maxim Turbulenc record.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on baking sheets, but from a quality point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues baking tapes, then you probably dream of such a record player.
This is similar to the one intended for travel, i.e. compressed - simplified with MP3 music.
There are also price and quality categories here.
For some, it may be unacceptable to issue eight thousand crowns for a player, as a Pink Floyd fan is likely to find it difficult to accept a 20-crown market listener.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The lifespan of the elements also matters
Some top-notch music players are capable of much more than simply playing music, but also of something that most mobiles don’t even happen to.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone call and text messaging, you can also play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera, and even navigate.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV can take photos.
There are also drawbacks to multi-functional mobile.
The more features you use on your mobile phone, the more times the display sends to the charger.
And music playing is one of the biggest energy regulators.
Few mobile devices are able to play music for longer than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, the music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly higher in performance.
For low-cost mobiles, expect that they won’t be playing for you for more than a few hours.
In addition, if you’re even on the phone here, get a charger for your workplace for the sake of safety – this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players won’t have such a problem, even the worse ones will have at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one charge.
The next problem arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector and in addition, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, the music can be attached directly to the memory card, but only a few card readers struggle with miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod) for players, you don’t need any special software.
It is enough to charge the device from the computer with music via USB.
Most of the mobiles and players have already created their own music library based on the performer, the name of the album, the genre, or, for example, the user’s rating.
Some devices only depict a tree structure similar to Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are more manageable, mobiles know more
When selecting a specific device, you will be interested in the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output, and of course the convenience of the treatment.
If your music primarily serves as a background for you and you only listen to it for a short time each day, for example, on the power station, any MP3 player mobile is also suitable for you.
In fact, any cell phone can do that.
You don’t even have to pay particular attention to what music formats your mobile or player knows.
All MP3s will be played, and the vast majority of the music that will be coming to you will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most widely used, and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices also cope with WMA-format music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and iPod) is less common.
Better mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit the appropriate pages of the provider (or other provider) through the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This service in itself can be a compelling argument for the acquisition of a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the provider’s offer is vague and usually limited to one-year radio waves.
The prices are not the lowest.
In general, however, it can be assumed that such a mode of sale of music (either on GSM, the Internet, or over the wireless Internet) will dominate the music market in the future.
The majority of people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever you want to listen to something, your mobile will pop out of your pocket while the forgotten MP3 player is hovering at home.
However, it still depends on whether you are always carrying the headphones or at least the speakers with you.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker that almost every mobile phone has, but only a few MP3 players.
For many, music mobiles will probably be the biggest advantage of the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand kronor.
Between three and four thousand crowns, you can get a decent walkman.
However, most of the time, you are limited by the lack of a traditional listener’s output.
The best and most equipped phones from the technical point of view can reach up to fifteen thousand crowns with the traditional 3.5 mm diameter hole earphones.
At the same time, the advantage of the players is the ease of handling.
The simplest - by no means necessarily with the treatment of the cheapest players (see our selection) really everyone is struggling.
A minimal function, the previously usual handling similar to magno or gramophone, is obvious.
There is no threat of a breakdown in the form of a mobile internet that is accidentally turned on, nor of the huge account that follows it for data transmission.
Which device to choose
The cheapest phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have openings for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
The purchase of the appropriate card also includes a maximum of two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of up to 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with up to 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and even want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowont, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Irivert.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) you do not need to spend more than 1 100 kroons.
If you belong to the more demanding students, choose special mobile walkers (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, thus bringing the convenience of handling closer to the MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson has become the most popular in the industry, with its walkman-series mobiles having the same user interface as the separately sold MP3 players.
MP3 players of the above mentioned brands can provide the same service in the same price category up to 4,000 crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our providers offer practically the same services as their Western European partners.
However, there is one thing we lack here - a virtual provider that forces classic providers to significantly lower prices.
Maybe it won't be that long.
On Mobil.cz we have written many times that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
Following the latest move by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges, there may be a conflicting situation - some of the Czech mobile service providers' customers' SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper than those sent from their home countries.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to get into the fight.
This may sound contradictory, since we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile providers would like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, president of the Czech Telecommunications Office Council, has often agreed that there is no place for new providers in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classical provider probably does not have too many chances with its own network (but it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is one more option - the virtual provider.
The move by virtual providers to the mobile market has led to a significant drop in prices, after which classical providers have also had to react.
In the meantime, even before the big fish market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in the UK, sounds similar to ours were heard.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can truly be successful.
However, for example, we do not have to go too far.
This February, we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than half a year, this service provider has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, behind Mobilking is the Penta financial group, which owns the U:fon in the Czech Republic, among others.
The advantage of virtual providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate effectively, you need far fewer customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not have a relatively high cost of construction, mobile network management and maintenance.
Virtual providers in the world thus usually appear as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and text messages, which, however, are often counterbalanced by fewer services.
For example, the UK-based Tesco Mobile offers at least fifty percent cheaper text messages than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, a good draw can also be accepted for such a target group.
This service is specifically focused on men.
“The real men choose the Mobilking service provider – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether an idea similar to Poland can work out in our country.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD>, spokesperson for Vodafone, said: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which the majority of virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied in terms of the provision of services."
Unexpected in the Czech Republic, mobile service providers say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is some virtual provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic, the agreements do not seem too hopeful.
To start Mobilking is more likely to happen in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ko, a spokesman for the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz.
In doing so, he confirmed that the existing mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not too familiar with this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition can be created.
For some time now, the GTS Novara Group has not been keeping its interest in launching a virtual service provider, which would like to take another step towards making Telefonica O2 a true competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in not only providing our customers with wired, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner, the better.
We have discussed this possibility again and again with all Czech mobile providers.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
Maybe there's a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that for the first virtual provider, we may be lucky by the end of the year.
However, his birth is surrounded by an impenetrable listening wall.
“At the moment, we don’t think that a full-fledged virtual provider would have a place in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike the other markets, is very special.
So far, we have not been invited to a single, complex and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, press officer of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica 02, told Mobil.cz.
Other providers also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, spokesman for T-Mobile, said: “So far, we have not recorded a single viable and bilaterally advantageous business project on which we can continue to rely.”
And he added: “In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year it is unlikely that any virtual provider will appear.
At this moment, there should be a concrete agreement on our table so that we can think about it in such a short time."
Instead, Vodafone pays attention to meeting its own 3G licensing requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are excited about negotiations with possible virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
From the point of view of customers, this is what we consider to be the most cost-effective.
Vodafone’s main strategy is to partner in this area to build networks that share the fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - one line with the providers
The procedure of mobile service providers is easy to understand, the entry of another service provider would mean an increase in competition, a decrease in price and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why should we make it easier to enter such a competition?
When a service provider is able to work together on something important, it also bears witness to the chaos surrounding the birth of the U:phone.
The biggest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was probably the birth of T-Mobile’s U:phone.
This is evidenced by the information publicly available from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> website.
But right now, the U:fon comes up with a good argument as to why we don’t allow the virtual service provider to enter.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> added: "The environment of the mobile market's competition has recently been affected by the entry of the fourth mobile provider market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of a new player into the market and its services would be based on high requirements."
However, given the attitude of mobile service providers, the total disinterest of the Czech regulators is directly amazing.
Meanwhile, it is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other developed countries - has no right to interfere in the economic competition.
It is exclusively entitled to do so by the Economic Competition Authority.
But, of course, the office is related to the whole problem.
"The move to the mobile market of a virtual service provider would only be possible if the contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider were to be concluded on the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, since the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting to traditional providers," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chlapua, from the Department of External Relations of the Economic Competition Authority.
A statement made in this way from the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office, which should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one can live back to their market situation, it is more than strange.
Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “In a country where virtual providers usually work, we can see that our market share has contributed to the reduction in the price of mobile phone services.”
However, it is likely that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS’ interests do not fall under the pressure of the proper functioning of the market environment and of price reductions.
In this case, it is really shocking that the three mobile service providers’ reactions are completely compatible.
The question of whether it is really just an accident is almost self-evident.
Just as in filling stations, gasolines that are exactly the same are probably just works of random and hard competition.
"The Office has not disclosed the signs of the anti-competitive procedure in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the providers has a leading position, i.e. they do not have a proportionally greater responsibility for their market activities.
The tools needed to open the mobile market for virtual providers are likely to be missing from the telecommunications regulator as well," Chalupa said.
The presentation of the market leadership situation is one of the many points of discussion.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
After such a market, of course, there is not a single Czech provider in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different perspective - the creation of a virtual provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile service provider - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So, in a certain segment, it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we do not accept this argument, there should be a minimum incentive for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that three mobile service providers behave in a similar manner.
Meanwhile, the complaints of a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novara company) show that they encounter very similar obstacles during the course of the negotiations with all providers.
The reassignment of responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have met with this in a number of similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecommunications law, the extension of the scope of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not possible, although many experts hoped to improve the situation.
The representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS need to know this well, but they probably have other interests.
It works when no one is listening.
Meanwhile, the operation of some kind of virtual service providers remains unnoticed, many of which already operate in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
They are multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer against the provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an outstanding customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit similar prepayments.
"If there were any cases that we are talking about, it could be a breach of contract conditions that we are dealing with and which could lead to the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said in a statement.
But it is unlikely that news of this kind of activity would not have reached the people responsible for the mobile service providers.
In particular, the three companies mentioned can be referred to as several thousand customers.
In the meantime, no provider will defend against such a procedure.
Because of the activities of these companies, they do not have negligible profits, and, unlike real virtual providers, they do not, in particular, threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by the negligible percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card is not in their name on their phone, so they can’t have it in full, like the general customers of mobile service providers.”
But that's what the <0xC4><0x8C>TU should at least be curious about.
In addition, another question arises for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile service providers are faced with a similar procedure, why do they prevent the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be noted that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has a relatively strong right to disclose such activity and, if it does not want to, it should not be satisfied with the explanation of the providers that they have not done so and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market has led to a noticeable decrease in the price of services.
In the meantime, in virtually every country where virtual service providers were created, the classic service providers tried to prevent them from being created more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the developed countries, however, regulators intervened at this very moment, which in no way protected the interests of mobile service providers but their customers.
Then, either by formal measures or by informal pressure, they reached the conclusion that the first virtual provider was created, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators have given the whole case to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual provider is really coming up soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the providers would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS can hardly remain indifferent to the refusal of further interested parties (to discriminate).
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be able to make more expensive calls.
