Relapsed drinking drivers will be required to install the "Alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior, after a three-drink driving rule violation, would oblige the car to install a structure that would prevent the vehicle from starting if the driver is in an alcoholic state or does not blow into the structure.
The proposal was circulated in June and is currently being dealt with by the Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which the pilot project will take a year.
As the project aims to restore traffic, the driver will also have to take part in a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the General Directorate of Transport Safety (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Automotive Safety Technology (FITSA) participate in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75% of cars arrested several times due to drunk driving are sitting in the car again.
This would be prevented by the Alcoholock, since the system connected to the vehicle determines the level of the inhaled air. If it is larger than the permitted one, or if the driver does not blow into the device at all, the system does not allow to start the car.
The cost of the more than <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1000 instrument would be charged to the offender.
A study conducted in the US in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices could reduce the number of violations by as much as 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could save their lives every year.
The measure focuses on violations of the rules for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from committing crimes,
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce, since the implementation of the legal reform takes place in the usual medre, while the necessary criminal reform would require a fundamental amendment of the law.
The instrument is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although in experimental mode some industrial and utility vehicles have already been fitted.
