The tenth anniversary of the founding of Héma-Québec yesterday was a good reason for the celebration, because Héma-Québec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood-sucking companies in the world.
And most importantly, it has succeeded in regaining people’s trust, which was severely damaged by the blood-infested scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well-known, the national blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood transfusion service was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
After the drama and the general upsurge, the Government of Canada launched an official investigation in February 1994 under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever. Its purpose was to shed light on what circumstances led to the tragedy and to put forward proposals for the future.
While presenting a delayed report by Judge Krever, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has completed this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood-sucking services were established in Canada: one in Quebec serving Héma-Québec and the other in Canada's Blood-sucking Society responsible for the supply of all the other provinces and the two territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in the Quebec blood-sucking system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was deplorable.
"In the years to come, however, we have managed to regain people's trust as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field." Décary proudly reports that by the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the population in Quebec had already been able to trust Hécé.
Dr. Décary, however, does not forget that “trust is extremely fragile.”
Since the founding of Héma-Québec on 28 September 1998, the principle of caution has been applied.
During this period, there have been a number of cases in Europe where a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease has also infected people - says the doctor, who has managed the company since its inception in 1998.
"We didn't even know if the disease was spreading through the blood.
That is why we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to the fact that if we are uncertain in this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we should apply exclusive measures. In this case, the cause of the Creutzfeldt-Ja disease was
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not receive blood from people who have spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
A few years ago, however, all doubts were made that the disease spread even through the blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that makes HIV virus diagnosis much more sensitive. This is a nucleic acid test (NAT), which in the blood of blood clots is able to directly detect the virus, and not the antibodies that are formed against the virus, which are used in the testicles in the past.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can show the virus through our technical means in the blood - explained the specialist.
This period was able to be reduced for a shorter period of time than a week.
Thus, they significantly mitigated the risk of blood clots infecting the blood vessels beyond our control, as well as of not being able to show this.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of the spread of AIDS by the way of blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of someone getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“In a nutshell, this means that we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400-500,000 blood preparations every year, it should take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and someone to be infected with HIV through a blood preparation.
I think that today, anyone can take it easy or sign up for blood transfusions to restore health,” says the first-ever leader of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogens are entering the system.
It was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with an insect bite.
That's why we need to be constantly vigilant," continued Dr. Décary, and then stressed that, in addition to the emergency supplies, Héma-Québec has to take care of enough permanent supplies.
“As the population ages, so do the demands.
As anti-cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the blood supply, as the number of people in the network who are eligible for bleeding accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, any healthy person, who is at least 18 years old, can give blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not receive blood because they have been infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have been in a country where malaria is being eradicated have not been allowed to bleed for a year.
“With this 3 percent, we have enough reserves that we can meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare for us to get out of stock.
