Hema-Québec, which has a budget of $297 million per year, provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs, and personal tissue, which are rarely used.
These tissues are analysed, transformed and frozen, and then placed in Héma-Québec, which at the same time also manages a single public stem cell bank in Quebec.
The blood from the cervix treated only as a medical waste can be obtained, which is rich in stem cells, thus also allowing the treatment of serious diseases (e.g. leukemia).
“We celebrated a few weeks ago that we have entered our bank with the thousandth baby blood sample, and we plan to take more than a thousand new samples every year.
