The Psychology of Over-Citation: Why Do We Give Out More Money?
On pricing, buyers tend to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known — and seemingly irrational — behavior have been revealed to New York University neurologists and economists.
According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to compete in a type of competition, such as eBay auctioning, so they’re paying too high a price.
The research tried to map the nervous system diagram of this "play" with the help of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers participated in the lottery and the other group participated in the player auction, while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method, they examined the active brain areas of the experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which an important element is the overstatement of the other side - a complex called striatum, under the chin, became intensively operational when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the mechanism of the nervous system's "recognition" in addition to several other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase can be explained by avoiding the severe reaction of striatum.
To support their theory, the members of the research group of economists also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In these three groups, they bid against one partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product concerned and they made their bets.
Another group has also been promised that if they get out of the game, they will get another $15 in rewards.
The third group, however, received just $15 before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the money was also lost.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only so much that for one of them the gain was emphasized, for the other the loss was emphasized.
However, by proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team playing "against loss" were willing to bet higher than the control and "power" group.
“These results cannot be derived from the theory of any economy that has existed before.
So far, they have only explained the phenomena that can be experienced in the auction with the joy of winning and the avoidance of risk.
Only the neurological imaging methods have helped to resolve the contradiction between these two theories by reaching a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, among the leading causes of death, chronic liver disease is mentioned.
There are hundreds of thousands of people infected with hepatitis at home, but only seven thousand are treated for this reason: patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collection of infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
Their tonsils have many similarities, characteristic of inflammation of the liver and yellowness, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food chain (e.g., food contaminated, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (inflammation, swelling).
Travelers are definitely worth protecting against the A and B virus, there is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, usually accompanied by a bad feeling, weakness, abdominal complaint, nausea.
After this, yellowness appears on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stool becomes a light, the urine becomes a dark color, the healing can last for two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die of the most serious type of the disease, caused by hepatitis B in the liver and liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people will receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to hepatic insufficiency and liver failure.
Most infected people do not even know about his illness, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells subtly, in many cases the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Thus, then, it is very important to carry out early prevention, regular filtering tests.
In three groups, there are far more than average cases of this disease: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattoos.
The number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus in the world is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, it is worth going to the GP when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
In time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, so that the ability to infect and the development of cancer can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
It aims to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by viruses, the causes of its formation and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
