What would be the best way to develop technologies that are suitable for avoiding collisions if not the imitation of obstacles in the world of nature?
The bees, for example.
In the surprise project presented at CEETEC in Japan, the Dongo bees gave the strategic idea to Nissan engineers to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a BR23C-type, bioengineered car robot control system, a robotic mini-car that has been equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to design a system that will help to prevent the formation of a bee.
During the flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety protection cages, explained Kazuhhiro Doi, technology PR and research and development brand director at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the complex eye of the bee, which is able to see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
In order to print out the function of the complex eye, the engineers came up with the idea of a laser rangefinder.
This 180-degree field of view in front of the BR23C identifies the obstacles within a distance of 2 meters, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately forms an operation to avoid the collision.
During the fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, then the autorobot, following the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction of the wheels to the extent necessary to avoid the collision.
In any way different from the current system, this avoidant maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If it wasn’t, the car robot wouldn’t be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and project at the car robot.
It needs to react in an intuitive way and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the security buffers, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does in order to get rid of other bees.
This process needs to be done in a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards or transversely, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibility available to the bees to avoid the other bees, only the rotational movement and acceleration, as well as the slowing, were used as the option available to the vehicle.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and higher in energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than the lithium-ion variant.
According to Andoh, the instinctive intelligent response is the ability to process data, not the ability to store it even less.
This structure needs to process and respond to only a few input signals per second.
You don’t need to keep them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous manoeuvrings, so you constantly use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
You don't need a gigabyte of memory, or you don't need a megabyte of memory.
This is the first step in the development of the technology for immediate avoidance, which, according to Nissan’s estimate, can be involved in series-production cars within ten years.
Another application option may be to integrate the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system in order to steer the car to the specified destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
